    en: "NY ABLE is a tax-advantaged savings account for people with disabilities, run by the NY Office of the State Comptroller. Money in the account grows tax-free as long as it is used for qualified disability expenses. Federal law under 26 USC 529A (the Stephen Beck Jr. Achieving a Better Life Experience Act of 2014) created the program. NY's version is at My NY ABLE. Annual contributions up to the federal ABLE limit, with an additional ABLE-to-Work amount equal to the federal poverty line for an employed account holder, can be saved without losing Supplemental Security Income (SSI), Medicaid, or other means-tested benefits. Account balances up to a federal threshold do not affect SSI. Qualifying conditions: disability that began before age 46 (federal law was extended in 2026 from age 26) with severity meeting SSI or SSDI standards. Current limits and thresholds are at mynyable.org."
